@Barry Ancona

Indeed, not only am I a man and 2 dogs — one of those 2 dogs was lying in my lap for the full hour and change I spent solving the puzzle!

I guess I just fell in love with “preprints” and took quite a while to let go of it. (Also, “pre-code era” was among the handful of trivia entries that were totally opaque to me, which didn’t make matters any easier)

@Bill 
Thanks for explaining AAVE. I had no clue.
I’m also with you for 29D. CLASS ACT just didn’t have the right ring.

@Grant

STICKUM reminded me of the Rick Moranis classic Little Giants. The receiver slathers up only to find his hands stuck together after the post-huddle single clap.

(Once I remembered the name of the movie, it occurred to me that Moranis's filmography has a couple of Littles, a bunch of Shrunks, and a related Blew Up.)

@Eric 

Here in NYC, no small amount of our local legislation is set and administered at the state level: non-trivial issues such as the MTA and housing regulations, for example. 

This clue was a rare gimme for me in an otherwise tough, worthy puzzle!

@Eric 

My initial reaction was the same as yours, but G’s comments have me rethinking that a little. 

I drafted legislation for the Texas Legislature for years. The Texas Constitution prohibits the lege from passing “local laws,” but STATE REPS (and state senators) were forever asking us to drafting bills “bracketed” to a specific municipality. It’s easier for someone from Dallas to get a bill that affects only Dallas passed, because the members from the rest of the state usually don’t care.

@Eric Hougland 

So interesting! When @Eric mentioned El Paso, it brought to mind hearing in the news (this year? maybe last?) about the Texas STATE REPS passing (attempting to pass?) legislation targeting Houston and its liberal proclivities. 

Your comment sheds some light on how this could come to pass. Thanks!

@G 

That’s exactly what happens. 

The legislature used to frequently target Austin, but as Houston turned from red to blue, they turned their sights that way.

@Old, former Raiders fan 

I thought of him, too.  Also, wasn't Biletnikoff also famous for being all sticky?

You have my deepest sympathies concerning the Raiders and the Athletics.  Oakland is really mistreated by the major sports leagues.

@Super8ing About 1.7 billion years ago, in what is now Gabon, uranium ore apparently underwent natural nuclear fission. 

<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_nuclear_fission_reactor" target="_blank">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Natural_nuclear_fission_reactor</a>

I didn't like the clue either, but wanted to share a link to this rather remarkable phenomenon.

@Emilie 

I thought today's Spelling Bee was great — lots of uncommon words to find.

I needed five guesses for Wordle. It's not my favorite game and I don't usually play as analytically as I should. And it annoys me to reach a spot where, say, you have four letters in green, three guesses left, and there's four or five equally plausible possibilities.

@Iliveaboard

I always forget that switching out of Hard Mode midstream is an option. 

I actually don’t play Wordle often. I don’t think I have ever learned a new word from playing it.

@Lynn 

A rim attaches to a tire the same way it attaches to a hubcap.  The tire attaches to the rim, not the other way around. 

This really is an attempt to be clever - but still wrong.
